{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b56bf23a-1f4f-4b7f-acba-9d9a516e94bb","content":"I'd be happy to help guide you through analyzing a .NET crash dump. Here are your main options:\n\n### 1. **WinDbg + SOS** (Windows)\n```bash\n# Load dump, then in WinDbg:\n.loadby sos coreclr        # Load SOS extension\n!clrstack                  # Managed call stack\n!pe                        # Print last exception\n!dumpheap -stat            # Heap summary\n!threads                   # All managed threads\n```\n\n### 2. **dotnet-dump** (Cross-platform)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nThen inside the REPL:\n```\n> clrstack\n> pe                        # Print exception\n> dumpheap -stat\n> clrthreads\n```\n\n### 3. **lldb + SOS** (Linux/macOS)\n```bash\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\nplugin load libsosplugin.so\nsos clrstack\nsos pe\n```\n\n### Key commands to find root cause:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` | Shows the exception that caused the crash |\n| `clrstack` | Stack trace of the current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | Lists all threads (look for exceptions) |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n\n**Want me to help further?** If you can upload or place the `.dmp` file in this directory, I can run `dotnet-dump analyze` on it directly. Otherwise, start with `pe` (print exception) — it's usually the fastest path to root cause.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2b6bb169-562d-424b-ad97-2a6212d31c60","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for help analyzing a .NET crash dump (.dmp file). This is a general knowledge question about debugging techniques - they haven't provided the file or pointed to one in the workspace. Let me give them practical guidance on how to analyze it.\n\nLet me check if there's anything relevant in the current working directory first.","outputTokens":480,"requestId":"502D:2C454F:278397:31E02C:69F555CB"},"id":"9c445ac1-f7e3-47fc-a8e8-eaf9584c777e","timestamp":"2026-05-02